{
  "answer": "**\"Taleem aur iske Nataaij\"** (\"Education and Its Consequences\"), from *Bang-e-Dara Part 3*, is a short critique of modern (Western-influenced) education. Iqbal notes pleasure in youth's progress but laments its unforeseen result: godlessness.[^1] A representative stanza:\n\n> We too are pleased with the progress of our youth, but  \n> from these smiling lips, a lament escapes as well.  \n> We once believed education would bring solace and liberty;  \n> who knew that godlessness would come along with it?[^2]\n\n**Part 1 of *Bang-e-Dara*** contains numerous children's poems—prayers, fables, and dialogues—that *enact* an alternative: spiritual formation rooted in Islamic values, wonder at divine creation, moral discernment, and selfless aspiration. Examples include \"Bachay Ki Dua\" (A Child's Prayer), \"Bacha aur Shama\" (Child and Candle), and \"Ek Makra aur Makhi\" (A Spider and a Fly). These model education as unveiling inner divine light through prayer, beauty, and cautionary wisdom, countering the \"godlessness\" critiqued elsewhere.\n\nA stanza from \"Bachay Ki Dua,\" a child's prayer for a life of illuminating service:\n\n> My deepest longing comes to my lips as a prayer:  \n> O God, may my life be like a candle's flare.  \n> May my life's spark dispel the darkness of the world,  \n> May my shining light in every place be unfurled.[^3]\n\nNo, the *formation* described in the theory is **not** the same as that performed in the poems. The theory describes a *negative* formation: modern education's hybrid of material progress and spiritual emptiness (\"solace and liberty\" tainted by \"godlessness\"), which Iqbal rejects, urging a fresh \"seed.\"[^4] The Part 1 poems, by contrast, *perform* the positive formation he desires—*khudi* (selfhood) as God-centered light, moral vigilance, and communal pride—instilling faith *before* knowledge to avoid the pitfalls he diagnoses.[^5]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 22 \"Taleem aur iske Nataaij\" ([paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/22-taleem-aur-iske-nataaij/translation/#p-485136)).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 22 \"Taleem aur iske Nataaij\" ([paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/22-taleem-aur-iske-nataaij/translation/#p-da36f6)).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 16 \"Bachay Ki Dua\" ([paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/16-bachay-ki-dua/translation/#p-28b7ba)).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 22 \"Taleem aur iske Nataaij\" ([paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/22-taleem-aur-iske-nataaij/translation/#p-2f0781)).\n\n[^5]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 15 \"Bacha aur Shama\" ([paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/15-bacha-aur-shama/translation/#p-a036dd)).",
